rceptions of Islam as a conservative practise, with stringent regulations for women in particular, Joseph Hill reveals how women integrate values typically associated with pious Muslim women into their leadership. These female leaders present spiritual guidance as a form of nurturing motherhood; they turn acts of devotional cooking into a basis of religious authority and prestige; they connect shyness, concealing clothing, and other forms of feminine “self-wrapping” to exemplary piety, hidden knowledge, and charismatic mystique. Yet like Sufi mystical discourse, their self-presentations are profoundly ambiguous, insisting simultaneously on gender distinctions and on the transcendence of gender through mystical unity with God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aSenegal.  aShaykh Ibrahim Niasse.  aSufism.  aTijaniyya.  aWest Africa.  agender.  aperformance.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751701440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517014423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517014.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles